(Beginner) Quest 3 - Hedera Developer Fundamentals
Introduction
In this quest, we’ll first cover some of the SDKs that are available on Hedera. Then, we’ll be introducing you to the Hedera Hashgraph SDK, which will be the main SDK we’ll be using for the remainder of this campaign. 
In particular, for this quest, we’ll be learning how we can use the SDK to create an account and transfer HBAR from one account to another, similar to what we did using the HashPack wallet in the previous quest!

For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #hedera-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
  • Describe SDKs that are available on Hedera
  • Initialise a Hedera development environment
  • Programmatically create an account and transfer HBAR between accounts
Deliverable
This quest has one deliverable.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Hedera SDKs
There exists several software development kits (SDKs) in Hedera - they can be categorized by their use cases and the programming languages they support. Listed below are the SDKs available for each use case.
Hedera Network Services SDKs
Hedera provides several SDKs that allow developers to interact with the Hedera network. Currently, the programming languages supported are Java, Javascript, Go and Swift. Apart from these, there are also SDKs that have been created and maintained by the community. These include the Hedera SDK for .NET and the Hashgraph Venin SDK for JS.

Ecosystem Wallet Support
The following are SDKs that are used for providing wallet support when it comes to integrating with the Hedera ecosystem. Both of these SDKs are maintained by the Hedera community. These SDKs are Blade Wallet Javascript API and HashPack HashConnect.

Decentralized Identity SDKs
These SDKs are used to facilitate decentralized identities into Hedera applications. In particular, they’re used to manage DID documents and verifiable credentials registration (abiding by W3C standards), all powered via the Hedera Consensus Service. These SDKs are the Hedera Java DID SDK and Hedera Javascript DID SDK.

Serverless SDKs
The last category of SDKs allow developers to build a Hedera-powered application using their own serverless REST client. There are two SDKs available to choose from - Serverless Hedera REST API and Serverless Hedera Laravel Package.
Step 2: Initialising Node.js Project
In this quest, we’ll be interacting with the Hedera network extensively using the Hedera Hashgraph SDK. To do so, we first need to set up our development environment.
We’ll first start by creating a new project directory - let's open up our terminal and run the commands below - these commands will create a new directory called stackup-hedera and enter into the directory.

mkdir stackup-hedera && cd stackup-hedera

Since we’ll be initializing a Node.js project, you’ll need to have Node.js installed on your machine before proceeding. To check if you have Node.js installed, run the following command in your terminal.
 
node -v
 
If it is already installed, a version number should be returned. We recommend a Node.js version of 14 and above. If your version of Node.js is lower than that, refer here for a guide on how to update your Node.js version.

Now let’s go ahead and initialize our Node.js project. Run the command below in your terminal to do so.

npm init --yes

After running the command, you should see that a package.json file has been created in your directory. If you open up package.json using a code editor, you’ll see that there are currently no dependencies involved (refer to image in ‘Expected output’). We’ll be installing the project dependencies in the next step!
Expected output
Step 3: Installing Project Dependencies
Now that our empty Node.js project has been instantiated, we need to install the dependencies that we’ll be using for this project. There are two main libraries we’ll be using - Hedera Javascript SDK and DotEnv.
Hedera Javascript SDK
This is the library that contains all the functions that we’ll be using to interact with the Hedera network. We can install this library by running the command below in our terminal.

npm install --save @hashgraph/sdk

Dotenv
Dotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a .env file into process.env. By using Dotenv, we can store all our sensitive information into a file called .env and read information from that file whenever needed, removing the need for us to hardcode sensitive information directly to our scripts. 

When code is pushed to a central repository such as Github, we typically add .env to the gitignore file, thus keeping our sensitive information private since the .env file does not get pushed to the shared repository. Let’s go ahead and install this library by running the command below in our terminal.

npm install dotenv

If you look at your package.json file now, you’ll see these two new dependencies have been added to your Node.js project. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference.
Expected output
Step 4: Importing Developer Portal Account Information
In the next few steps, we’ll be making use of the Hedera Developer Portal account created in Quest 2. If you haven’t finished Quest 2 yet, please do so before continuing with this step.
Head to the Hedera Developer Portal. We’ll be making use of the ‘ED25519 DER Encoded Private Key’ and ‘ED25519 Account ID’ information for the subsequent steps. But where should we store these pieces of information in our project? Hint: the answer can be found in Step 3.

If you figured it out, then congrats! We’ll be storing these two pieces of information in a file called .env and reading from it using the Dotenv library. Let’s create a file called .env in our root repository - we can do so in our terminal by running the command below.

touch .env

Note that the file we just created is a hidden file, so you might not be able to see it in your directory right away. If you can’t see the file, depending on the operating system of your computer, chose one of the following guides to enable your computer to display hidden files - Mac Windows Linux. Then, paste the code below into the .env file you just created. 

MY_PRIVATE_KEY = REPLACE-WITH-YOUR-PRIVATE-KEY MY_ACCOUNT_ID = REPLACE-WITH-YOUR-ACCOUNT-ID

Replace REPLACE-WITH-YOUR-PRIVATE-KEY and REPLACE-WITH-YOUR-ACCOUNT-ID with your Hedera Developer Portal account’s ED25519 DER Encoded Private Key and ED25519 Account ID respectively. Refer to the image in ‘Expected output’ for a reference.
Expected output
Step 5: Overview of Project
Now that our project environment is set up, let’s go ahead and start on the actual script that contains the code we’ll be using to create an account and transfer HBAR from one account to another. We’ll be creating another file in our root repository called create-acc-transfer-hbar.js. We can do so by running the command below in our terminal.
touch create-acc-transfer-hbar.js

After that, open the script using a code editor of your choice, copy the code below and paste it in.

const { Client } = require("@hashgraph/sdk"); require("dotenv").config(); const createAccTransferHbar = async () => {  // Part 1 - Grab Hedera testnet account  const myAccountId = process.env.MY_ACCOUNT_ID;  const myPrivateKey = process.env.MY_PRIVATE_KEY;  if (myAccountId == null || myPrivateKey == null) {   throw new Error("account ID or Private key are missing");  }  // Part 2 - Create connection to the Hedera network  // Part 3 - Create new account  // Part 4 - Get the new account's ID  // Part 5 - Verify the new account's starting balance  // Part 6 - Transfer 250 TINYBARs from Hedera Testnet account to new account  // Part 7 - Verify the new account's current balance }; createAccTransferHbar();

The comments in the code describe the steps that we’ll be completing in the subsequent steps. Essentially, Parts 1 to 5 refer to creating a new account whereas Parts 6 and 7 refer to transferring HBAR tokens from one account to another. Ready? Let’s go!
Step 6: Creating Hedera Testnet Client
Part 1 - Grab Hedera testnet account We start by grabbing the account information of our Hedera Testnet account using the process.env syntax. We then check to see if either of them are null - if either of them are, then an error message will be thrown. You do not need to add this into your script as it has already been added for you.

Part 2 - Create connection to the Hedera network
Now we’ll need to create a Hedera Testnet client. The client is the software that interacts with the Hedera network. This client would be responsible for providing a secure way of signing transactions, submitting transactions, querying the state of the network and receiving transaction and network updates.

Creating a client requires an account’s ID and private key, the latter is used to securely sign transactions. The account ID is used to identify the account whereas the account private key is used to securely sign transactions, ensuring authenticity. Note that we can choose to create a client for either the Hedera mainnet or testnet. In our case, we’ll be creating one for the testnet.

const client = Client.forTestnet(); client.setOperator(myAccountId, myPrivateKey);

Copy the code above and paste it under // Part 2 - Create connection to the Hedera network in your script. We create the Hedera testnet client with Client.forTestnet(). After creating the Hedera testnet client, we need to set the operator information. This operator will handle the account that will pay for the transaction and query fees. We do so using the client.setOperator() syntax. Since we’ll be using our Hedera testnet account, we pass in its information as arguments into the function.
Step 7: Creating an Account
In Quest 2, we created two accounts - the first being the Hedera Developer Portal account and the second one being the one we created using the Hashpack wallet. Now we’ll be creating another account, but doing so programmatically instead!
Part 3 - Create new account
const newAccountPrivateKey = PrivateKey.generateED25519(); const newAccountPublicKey = newAccountPrivateKey.publicKey; const newAccount = await new AccountCreateTransaction()   .setKey(newAccountPublicKey)   .setInitialBalance(Hbar.fromTinybars(1000))   .execute(client);

Copy the code above and paste it under // Part 3 - Create new account in your script. First, we generate a new private key using PrivateKey.generateED25519() - this will be the private key of our new account. Then, we generate the private key’s corresponding public key using the .publicKey method.

Lastly, we create a new account using AccountCreateTransaction(). We associate the set of keys (public & private keys) with the new account using .setKey(). 

Since we want this account to be created with some testnet HBAR in it, we fund the account using our Hedera testnet account. We do so using .setInitialBalance(). Let’s set the initial balance to be 1000 TINYBARs. Note that 1 HBAR = 1,000,000 TINYBARs, refer here for more information. Thus, we need to use Hbar.fromTinybars(1000) to configure this accordingly. 

Lastly, we fire off the transaction to the Hedera network with the .execute() command, passing in client as its argument.
Step 8: Get Account Information
At this point in our code, our new account would have been created. Before we test out our script, let’s go ahead and complete Parts 4 and 5 so that we can see certain pieces of information regarding our newly created account!
Part 4 - Get the new account's ID
const getReceipt = await newAccount.getReceipt(client); const newAccountId = getReceipt.accountId; console.log("The new account ID is: " + newAccountId);

Copy the code above and paste it under // Part 4 - Get the new account’s ID in your script. Let’s first get the account ID of our newly created account. We can attain the account ID from the receipt of the account creation transaction. We’ll use the .getReceipt() method for this. Since the receipt contains other information (besides the account ID) about the transaction, we’ll specifically pick out the account ID information using .accountId. Finally, we log the account ID so that we can view it in our terminal output when we run the script.

Part 5 - Verify the new account's starting balance
In the previous step, we set the initial balance of the new account to be 1,000 TINYBARs. Now let’s verify if the new account indeed does start with 1,000 TINYBARs.

const accountBalance = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(newAccountId).execute(client); console.log("The new account starting balance is: " + accountBalance.hbars.toTinybars() + " TINYBARs");

Copy the code above and paste it under // Part 5 - Verify the new account's starting balance in your script. Essentially, we can query for an account’s balance using .AccountBalanceQuery() and inputting the account ID.

Now let’s try running our script! We can do so by running the command below in our terminal.

node create-acc-transfer-hbar.js




It seems like we’ve run into an error! The reason for this error is because we’ve used a bunch of modules from the Hedera Javascript SDK but we’ve yet to import them into our script. To fix this, replace the first line in your script with the code below.

const { Client, PrivateKey, AccountCreateTransaction, AccountBalanceQuery, Hbar } = require("@hashgraph/sdk");

Now try running the script again. If you’ve followed along correctly till now, you should get an output similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. Here, we can see that our code has worked as intended - you’ve created a new account with an account ID that’s shown in your terminal output and that account is funded with 1,000 TINYBARs. Cool!

Troubleshooting: If you don’t get any output in your terminal after running the command, check the following:
  • Wrong terminal directory - ensure that your terminal is in the stackup-hedera folder. If it’s not, you can change its directory by typing cd stackup-hedera in the terminal
  • File not saved - ensure that you’ve saved the create-acc-transfer-hbar.js file after you’re done adding in all the required code

Step 9: Transferring HBAR
Great job following along so far! Time for the last portion of this quest - transferring HBAR from one account to another. More specifically, we’ll be transferring 250 TINYBARs from our Hedera testnet account to the newly created account.
Part 6 - Transfer 250 TINYBARs from Hedera Testnet account to new account
const sendHbar = await new TransferTransaction()   .addHbarTransfer(myAccountId, Hbar.fromTinybars(-250)) // Sending account   .addHbarTransfer(newAccountId, Hbar.fromTinybars(250)) // Receiving account   .execute(client); const transactionReceipt = await sendHbar.getReceipt(client); console.log("Status of transfer transaction: " + transactionReceipt.status.toString());

Copy the code above and paste it under // Part 6 - Transfer 250 TINYBARs from Hedera Testnet account to new account in your script. We transfer HBAR using the TransferTransaction() function. We specify the sending account and receiving account using the .addHbarTransfer() syntax. Note that the values passed into the .addHbarTransfer() parameters have to be the same, failing which an error message will be thrown.

After executing the transfer transaction, we get the transaction receipt with .getReceipt(), same as what we did when we created the account. Then, we log the status of the transaction so that we can view it in our terminal output.

Part 7 - Verify the new account's current balance
const newAccountBalance = await new AccountBalanceQuery().setAccountId(newAccountId).execute(client);  console.log("The new account current balance is: " + newAccountBalance.hbars.toTinybars() + " TINYBARs"); console.log(“Submission made by: REPLACE-WITH-STACKUP-USERNAME”);

Copy the code above and paste it under // Part 7 - Verify the new account's current balance in your script. Nothing new to cover here, it’s basically a repeat of what we did in Part 5. Make sure to replace REPLACE-WITH-STACKUP-USERNAME with your StackUp username. Note that if your syntax highlighter is prompting an “invalid character” error, try to retype the double quotation marks ” ” yourself after pasting in the code.

Before we can proceed to test out our script, we’ll need to import the TransferTransaction module into our script since we used it in Part 6. To do so, add TransferTransaction to the array of imported modules in line 1.

Now let’s try running our script again! As a refresher, we can do so by running the command below in our terminal.

node create-acc-transfer-hbar.js

If you’ve completed the step correctly, you should get an output similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. From the terminal output, we can see that our newly created account starts off with a balance of 1000 TINYBARs, but after the successful transfer transaction, the balance has increased to 1250 TINYBARs. Awesome!
